
  SSH into your EC2 instance and run:

  # Install Docker
  sudo yum update -y          # Amazon Linux / sudo apt update for Ubuntu
  sudo yum install -y docker  # or sudo apt install -y docker.io
  sudo systemctl start docker
  sudo systemctl enable docker
  sudo usermod -aG docker $USER

  # Log out and back in for group to take effect, then:

  # Login to GHCR (create a GitHub PAT with read:packages scope)
  docker login ghcr.io -u YOUR_GITHUB_USERNAME -p YOUR_GITHUB_PAT

  # Create env file directory
  mkdir -p ~/rag-app

  # Create your .env file on the server
  nano ~/rag-app/.env
  # Paste all your env vars from your local .env file

  3. GitHub Secrets

  Go to your repo → Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions and add these secrets:    

  ┌──────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │    Secret    │                       Value                        │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ EC2_HOST     │ Your EC2 public IP or domain (e.g. 54.123.45.67)   │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ EC2_USERNAME │ SSH user (e.g. ubuntu or ec2-user)                 │
  ├──────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ EC2_SSH_KEY  │ Your EC2 private key (the full .pem file contents) │
  └──────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  GITHUB_TOKEN is automatically available — no need to add it.

  4. Make Your GHCR Package Public (optional)

  If your repo is private, the image is private by default. The EC2 docker login step    
  handles auth. If you want it public, go to GitHub → Packages → Package settings →      
  Change visibility.

  5. Deploy

  Just push to main:

  git add .
  git commit -m "Add Docker and CI/CD pipeline"
  git push origin main

  The workflow will:
  1. Build your Docker image
  2. Push it to ghcr.io/your-username/rag_project:latest
  3. SSH into your EC2, pull the new image, and restart the container

  ---
  Important notes:
  - Your .env file lives only on the EC2 server at ~/rag-app/.env — never in the repo    
  - Make sure EC2 security group allows inbound on port 5000 (and 22 for SSH)
  - If you need a package-lock.json (you likely do for npm ci), run npm install locally  
  first to generate it, then commit it